ntfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"about 1005–about 1030":"circa 1005–circa 1030","1005–1030":"1005–1030","0988–1040":"0988–1040","1025–1100":"1025–1100","0942–1023":"0942–1023","0942":"0942","about 1030":"circa 1030","1005":"1005","1025":"1025","1023":"1023","1100":"1100","about 1025":"circa 1025","about 1005":"circa 1005","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","about 1023":"circa 1023","0988":"0988","Neufmarche, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Turqueville, Manche, Normandie, Frankrijk","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Brionne, Eure, Normandy, France":"Brionne, Eure, Normandie, Frankrijk","Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Upper Normandy, France":"Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1005–about 1030":"about 1005–about 1030","1005–1030":"1005–1030","0988–1040":"0988–1040","1025–1100":"1025–1100","0942–1023":"0942–1023","0942":"0942","about 1030":"about 1030","1005":"1005","1025":"1025","1023":"1023","1100":"1100","about 1025":"about 1025","about 1005":"about 1005","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","about 1023":"about 1023","0988":"0988","Neufmarche, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Turqueville, Manche, Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Brionne, Eure, Normandy, France":"Brionne, Eure, Normandy, France","Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Upper Normandy, France":"Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Montfort","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Breton: variant of   Monfort   1. This surname is most common in Brittany and Haute-Savoie. See also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>: habitational name from Montfoort in Utrecht. It is a cognate of 1 above (see   Monfort   1) and also its altered form (or perhaps vice versa).","English (of Norman origin): very rare variant of   Mountford  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Monfort","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Jacques, Marcel, Monique, Wilner.","French and Breton: habitational name from any of numerous places called Montfort, from Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ (see   Mont   1) + <i>fort</i> ‘strong, impregnable’ (from Latin <i>fortis</i>). This surname is by far most common in Brittany. It is also found in Haiti. Compare   Montfort   1, see also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>, a variant of   Montfort   2 and also a cognate of the French name in 1 above and an altered form of its variant   Montfort   1 (or perhaps vice versa)."]},{"name":"Monforte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmela, Carmine, Rocco, Rosaria, Sal.  Spanish Carlos, Francisco, Luis, Medardo.","Italian and Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Monforte, from Latin <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ (genitive <i>montis</i>) + <i>fortis</i> ‘strong’, probably a reference to the strategic position of these locations.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Montfort  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Adeline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["diminutive of <i>Adèle</i> (  see  Adele  ), used occasionally in England from the early 16th century onwards, and now also found in the wider English-speaking world."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Adeline de Montfort was born about 1005, in Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Upper Normandy, France as the daughter of THURSTAN BASTEMBOURG. She had at least 1 son with Turquetil or Thurketill de Neufmarché. She died about 1030, in Brionne, Eure, Normandy, France, at the age of 27."},"et":{"about 1005–about 1030":"umbes 1005–umbes 1030","1005–1030":"1005–1030","0988–1040":"0988–1040","1025–1100":"1025–1100","0942–1023":"0942–1023","0942":"0942","about 1030":"umbes 1030","1005":"1005","1025":"1025","1023":"1023","1100":"1100","about 1025":"umbes 1025","about 1005":"umbes 1005","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","about 1023":"umbes 1023","0988":"0988","Neufmarche, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Turqueville, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Brionne, Eure, Normandy, France":"Brionne, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Upper Normandy, France":"Montfort-sur-Risle, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1005–about 1030":"noin 1005–noin 1030","10